## R code 16.2

    alist(
        w ~ dlnorm( mu , sigma ),

16M3

Use prior predictive simulations to investigate the Lynx-hare model. Begin with the priors in the chapter. Which population dynamics do these produce? Can you suggest any improvements to the priors, on the basis of your simulations?

data(Lynx_Hare)

Priors from the stan model

// priors
  theta[{1,3}] ~ normal( 1 , 0.5 );    // bh,ml
  theta[{2,4}] ~ normal( 0.05, 0.05 ); // mh,bl
  sigma ~ exponential( 1 );
  pop_init ~ lognormal( log(10) , 1 );
  p ~ beta(40,200);
  // observation model
  // connect latent population state to observed pelts
  for ( t in 1:N )
    for ( k in 1:2 )
      pelts[t,k] ~ lognormal( log(pop[t,k]*p[k]) , sigma[k] );
}
generated quantities {
  real pelts_pred[N,2];
  for ( t in 1:N )
    for ( k in 1:2 )
      pelts_pred[t,k] = lognormal_rng( log(pop[t,k]*p[k]) , sigma[k] );

I think we want to give the simulation code initial populations and have it predict observed over time

update simulation code (note that order of theta is different here than in the stan code)

sim_lynx_hare <- function( n_steps=1e4 , init , theta , sigma, p, dt=0.002 ) {
    L <- rep(NA,n_steps)
    H <- rep(NA,n_steps)
    Lobs <- rep(NA, n_steps)
    Hobs <- rep(NA, n_steps)
    L[1] <- init[1]
    H[1] <- init[2]
    Lobs[1] <- rlnorm(1, ifelse(p[1]*L[1] < 0, 0, log(p[1]*L[1])), sigma[1])
    Hobs[1] <- rlnorm(1, ifelse(p[2]*H[1] < 0, 0, log(p[2]*H[1])), sigma[2])
    for ( i in 2:n_steps ) {
        H[i] <- H[i-1] + dt*H[i-1]*( theta[1] - theta[2]*L[i-1] )
        L[i] <- L[i-1] + dt*L[i-1]*( theta[3]*H[i-1] - theta[4] )
        Lobs[i] <- rlnorm(1, ifelse(p[1]*L[i] < 0, 0, log(p[1]*L[i])), sigma[1])
        Hobs[i] <- rlnorm(1, ifelse(p[2]*H[i] < 0, 0, log(p[2]*H[i])), sigma[2])
    }
    return( tibble(L_pop=L,H_pop=H,L_obs=Lobs,H_obs=Hobs,step=1:n_steps) )
}
init <- c(12.12, 3.81)
p <- c(0.174, 0.127)
sigma <- c(0.705, 1.74)
theta <- c(1.323, 0, 0.104, 0.299)

## R code 16.14
sim_lynx_hare <- function( n_steps , init , theta , dt=0.002 ) {
    L <- rep(NA,n_steps)
    H <- rep(NA,n_steps)
    L[1] <- init[1]
    H[1] <- init[2]
    for ( i in 2:n_steps ) {
        H[i] <- H[i-1] + dt*H[i-1]*( theta[1] - theta[2]*L[i-1] )
        L[i] <- L[i-1] + dt*L[i-1]*( theta[3]*H[i-1] - theta[4] )
    }
    return( cbind(L,H) )
}
